Yea, well your question refers to the older thread concerning the
dom7#9 businesses. Forgive all the wordage:

Again, I never share my knowledge with anyone without recommending to
research for an origin. I would first &quot;auto-harmonize&quot; (that is to
harmonize the chords utilizing the notes from the scale, stacking in
thirds; as you do with the tonal and modal voicings produced on major
and minor scales) the W/H diminished scale (the &quot;origin&quot;). Every
*other* chord within your resultants will produce your H/W diminished
field. Some call these resultants, the &quot;diminished-dominant chords&quot;
and their usage is all too common. You may have heard of the &quot;double-
diminished&quot; chord? This is what you come up with if you keep &quot;going
and going&quot; in building your tertian chord stack. The upper partials of
your staff-built voicing will give you another diminished chord a half
step apart from the first one; with tones that ironically clash with
the bottom of the staff generated voicing. This being the case, it is
necessary to readjust voicings, via octave displacement, in order to
establish chord coalition (a term I borrowed from studying
Persichetti). This adjusted voicing produces the voicing I laid out in
the previous discussion, for example from a G root-bass to soprano: G
B D F Ab A# C# E. The juxtaposing of the b9 and #9 is the only detour
from the pure third stacking fashion. The &quot;symetricality&quot; of the
origin scale warrants this. And this chord resultant has been adjusted
from what the diminished voicing yields &quot;instinctually&quot; as a chord
stack. In other words, we displace intervals by shifting their
locations in the chord stack: the &quot;flat 11th&quot; (the interval that
automatically comes out as an upper partial) now becomes the major 3rd
(by shifting to the lower section of the voicing) and the minor third
(which automatically appears in the second note from the bottom of the
staff-generated voicing) is now jettisoned up to become a sharp 9.
Every other chord, of course in the H/W scale, will produce the
original full diminished chord voicing (no adjustment), as those
positions are born of the bottom partial yield and are &quot;true&quot;
diminished chords. Natural ninth appears in that voicing, as opposed
to altered ninths in the H/W yield. Suddenly you have a b13 and a
natural 11th in the W/H yield to the opposite in the H/W yield. This
is the beauty of the beast-of-dissonance; using the both fields
together to make good music. It would take a mathematician to hip us
to all the theoretical possibilities concerning usage, but music is
spoken here and so, if you want to utilize the two harmonic fields
which are inherently generated form the double diminished chord stack,
I would go on to study the likely uses of diminished chords, for
example # I dim travels well to a ii-7 chord, # 2 dim to a ii-7 chord,
etc and use this in conjunction with your altered dominant resultants
(as one way to use the scale); for example G7 (b9,#9,#11,13) careening
with Abdim-maj (9,11,b13) ad infinitum. There are hundreds of hybrids
and chosen voicings (by deleting tones and/or auto-harmonizing using
clusters or Quartals), but I suggest studying the entire enchilada
first.

Hope this gives ideas for you.

-TD
