One of my fav tricks is using the triads based on the note a whole-step
above and a half-step below; i.e., the four triads a minor third apart.  Of
course you can use them in any inversion.

For example, on the scale you gave (Bb C Db Eb E F# G A Bb C Db Eb E F# G
A), using the following major triads:

C E G
A C# (Db) E
Gb (F#) Bb Db
Eb G Bb

a/k/a the chords C, Eb, Gb, A

You can also use a dominant 7th chord, but I usually like the sound of
triads better.

For example:

C E G Bb
A C#(Db) E G
Gb Bb Db Fb a/k/a F# A# C# E
Eb G Bb Db

a/k/a the chords C7, Eb7, Gb7, A7,

You can also use minor triads
C Eb G
A C E
F# A C#
Eb Gb Bb

a/k/a the chords C-, Eb-, Gb-, A-

And minor 7th chords too

C Eb G Bb
A C E G
F# A C# E
Eb Gb Bb Db

a/k/a the chords C-7, Eb-7, Gb-7, A-7

