On Aug 18, 7:53 am, &quot;cripe ... @aol.com&quot; &lt;cripe ... @aol.com&gt; wrote:

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; What does &quot;flying lead&quot; mean?
">

It's a term from big band arranging. It means that the chord is either
sustained, or repeated in rhythm with the melody. Meanwhile the horn
playing the top melody line flies above the rest of the horn section.
On piano, you can play block chord solos where every note moves up and
down under the melody, a la Shearing. Or you can just repeat the same
LH chord in rhythm with the RH melody. Big band arrangers will do the
same, and it also works on guitar.
