At the risk of being considered pedantic let me try to answer your
questions.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; It doesn't lead me to the double diminished. How do I get there with
&gt; stacking notes?
">

In a way you're right. The scale has 8 tones instead of 7 (I learned it as
octotonic HW scale), therefor by stacking thirds you go to the octave in 4
steps. However in a 7 tone scale after the 7 (or maj7 or b7) you would go
to a 9 (or b9 or #9). If you do that here too, you get to the b9 and by
further stacking you get the double diminished.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; The chord tones are C E G Bb Db.  If I think of it as C7#11 b9 #9 I get
&gt; C E F# Bb Db Eb. I can build voicings from those tones easily enough,
&gt; but what do I do with the G and A? Should I avoid them in comping?  Can
&gt; I really use any number of these 8 notes in a voicing and not make mud?
">

Actually the answer to this was in Tony's post. You can play all these 8
notes in your voicing, but the place in the cord stack is what matters.
the Db diminished on top of the C diminished clashes.

I learned this rule of tumb: a b9 interval in a chord sounds bad unless it
is on the root (b9) or on the 5 (b13). When you stack the Db diminished on
top of the C diminished you get four b9 intervals.

To avoid the unwanted b9 intervals between chord tones, you have to
change the place of some of the tones in the chord stack. Put the #9 above
the 3, the 13 (the b7 of your initial diminished chord) above the 7 and
the #11 above the 5 (usually you leave out the 5) That will give you the
dominant 7 b9 #9 #11 13 chord.

Hope this helps,

Guido
