Anyway that one wishes to really.
But the results of this type of an operation with an 8-note scale will
be quite different than the results you get with a typical 7-note scale
(i.e. a 7-note scale with no consecutive semitones).
The major and minor scales, when harmonized in 3rds, give us the main
chords used in the major/minor key system.
The chords you'll get from the harmonized dim scale are not key-related
in the same way.

If you harmonize the C w-h dim scale (C D Eb F Gb Ab A B C) in
scale-wise 3rds you'll get the following series of chords:

Cdim, Ddim, Ebdim, Fdim, Gbdim, Adim, Bdim, Cdim
Cdim7, Ddim7, Ebdim7, Fdim7, Gbdim7, Adim7, Bdim7, Cdim7

How, or if, you use those chords within a major or minor key will be up
to you, your sense of taste and your experience.

But usually, dim scale material is used on dom7b9 chords (h-w from the
root) and on dim7 chords (w-h from the root).
These chord-scale relationships yield a palette where there are no avoid
notes from the scale on the given chord.
h-w from the root of a dom7 chord will yield a dom7 chord with the
following extensions: b9, #9, #11, 13.
Eg. B7(b9,#9,#11,13)
w-h from the root of a dim7 chord will yield a dim7 chord with the
following extensions: 9, 11, b13, maj7.
Eg. Cdim7(9,11,b13,maj7)
I.e. All of the dim triads and dim7 chords listed above (and all of the
chords from the harmonized dim scale listed below) will &quot;blend in&quot; in
some fashion over B7b9, D7b9, F7b9, Ab7b9, Cdim7, Ebdim7, Gbdim7 and/or
Adim7.

If you start with these 3 notes:
D F# A - a D maj triad -
and harmonize the scale in parallel motion,
you'll get these chords:
D, Abm/Eb, F, Bm/F#, Ab, Dm/A, B, Fm/C, D

If you start with these 4 notes:
D F# A B - a D6 chord (or Bm7/D) -
and harmonize the scale in parallel motion,
you'll get these chords:
D6, Ab(add#9)/Eb, F6, B(add#9)/F#, Ab6, D(add#9)/A, etc.

If you start with C Eb Gb B [a Cdim(maj7) chord], you'll get:
Cdim(maj7), Dm7b5, Ebdim(maj7), Fm7b5, Gbdim(maj7), Abm7b5, etc.

If you start with C F B [&quot;F(sus#4)/C&quot;?, &quot;Cmaj7(sus4)(no5th&quot;?], you'll get:
Fsus#4, D7(no5th), Ebsus#4, F7(no5th), Gbsus#4, Ab7(no5th), etc.

Pick any 3 or 4 (or 5 etc.) scale tones you like.
Start with them and harmonize the scale in parallel motion and you might
find some sounds that you like over:
B7b9, D7b9, F7b9, Ab7b9, Cdim7, Ebdim7, Gbdim7 and Adim7.

Good luck.

