If you stack the notes of a 7-note scale in 3rds you'll use up all 7
notes. Not so with an 8-note scale.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I do understand that the diminished scale is composed of a four note
&gt; diminished chord 1 b3 b5 bb7 and the diminished chord a half step
&gt; below.
">

Better to think of it as a dim7 chord plus a dim7 chord a whole step above.
And a whole step above each chord tone of the lower dim7 chord you'll
find an available tension on that dim7 chord:

Eg. On Cdim7
A whole step above C you'll find T9.
A whole step above Eb you'll find T11.
A whole step above Gb you'll find Tb13.
A whole step above A you'll find T7.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; But, in trying to work out voicings for, say C7b9, the scale is C HW,
&gt; i.e.

&gt; C Db Eb E F# G A Bb.

&gt; The chord tones are C E G Bb Db.  If I think of it as C7#11 b9 #9 I
&gt; get C E F# Bb Db Eb. I can build voicings from those tones easily
&gt; enough, but what do I do with the G and A? Should I avoid them in
&gt; comping?  Can I really use any number of these 8 notes in a voicing
&gt; and not make mud?
">

This scale, when used on dom7b9 chords is not usually just simply
stacked in 3rds.
It might help clarify the relationships if you learn to think of C7b9 as
being Edim7/C and try to visualize the E w-h dim scale as being active
rather than the C h-w dim scale.
Then, you can see the chord tones of F#dim7 as being the added tensions
(except for the C of course) to the basic sound.
C E G Bb Db
plus
F# (#11) A (13) C and Eb (#9)

Again, the extended dom7 chord that the h-w scale yields is
dom7(b9,#9,#11,13).
It can be voiced all sorts of ways.
If you omit the #9, it can be seen as a tertian stack:
1 3 5 b7 b9 #11 13
But these are not *scale-wise* 3rds, at least not from the dim scale, as
you have noted.

Basically, for the most part, you'll need to abandon the paradigm of
stacks of scale-wise 3rds when you're working with harmonizations of
this scale. It's usually best to just pick a combination of scale tones
that you like the sound of and then just transpose them through the
scale, like I detailed in my other post in this thread.

