Like so:

bass to soprano: C Eb Gb A B D F Ab

It is stacked as you would a major chord, but you must understand that
it is a symetrical scale and you autoharmonize just like you do major,
but with the symetrical configuration in mind. You merely repeated the
first four notes. The extensions of that bottom chord form the top
chord. See it? Look at it from another viewpoint. Each extension is a
whole step away from the mother chord: C to D, Eb to F, Gb to Ab, A to
B. Now see the connection with the above stack. Cool?

Just as I had written about in prior posts concerning the stack for
the diminished dominant chord; all is in thirds except the major
second between the flat ninth and sharp ninth.

On the staff, this is how we generate the double diminished chord, by
writing that little detour from pure thirds, between C and B. The 2nd,
4th, 6th and 8th degrees give you: b7, b9, b11, 13.

As I had aforesaid, the extensions clash with the bottom voicing and
interval displacement becomes necessary.

