Perhaps, this subject will be a good one to hone in on with your
current teacher. By stacking the intervals in thirds (on the staff),
except for the seconds created by the altered ninths, you will *see*
the grand picture. Afterward, you will have better command of being
able to voice myriad chord shapes (mixing with clusters and augmented
shapes) in your own way and call upon them as you need them. You will
also understand what extensions and primary tones work together and
which ones do not; much depends on chord functioning.
For example, there are some cases where the b9 and #9 does *not*
function well together (most cases they function well together). And
*that* is a study which I highly recommend to work in concurrence with
this H/W diminished (and W/H) business. For another studying idea, I
suggest digging out the most obvious useful triads from the H/W realm.
Take major and minor from a G H/W: Gmaj Gmin Bbmaj Bbmin Dbmaj Dbmin
Emaj Eminor, but also study each enharmonic equivalent; for example
Gmaj will yield: b13, R, b3. G minor will yield b13, 7, b3. Why that?
Because, the B W/H is identical to the G H/W.
And I believe in utilizing the cycle of three, as good criteria for
this type of study. G is a major third below B. Some of us consider G
to be the &quot;harmonic root&quot; of B. Play B and sing G below and feel the
resonance inside your ears. W.A. Mathieu has a great book on this
stuff, The Harmonic Experience. Much can be learned there. The upper
partials of a C diminished will form B diminished, so there is no
small wonder that 'add' on notes can be a whole step away from each of
the chord tones. B diminished is enharmonically equivalent to D
diminished. When you are comfortable with major and minor triads drawn
from H/W dim, begin experimenting with clusters say bass to top using
G root: G-Ab-B, Ab-Bb-Db, A#-B-D, etc. Again utilize the concept of
enharmonic equivalents: G-Ab-B corresponds to B dim W/H as: b13, bb7,
b3.
After you are comfortable with clusters (&quot;Cluster's last stand&quot;) you
may want to move on to Quartals and polychords within the diminished
system. In other words, yea, study the chords by stacking thirds, but
realize that in practice you will need to utilize a mélange of
intervals. I can help you with that. Feel free to write me.

