">

So, once we establish the fact that a &quot;double-diminished&quot; chord
actually ( best to run to a piano) exists, as a result of diminished
chord coalition created by a marriage with the extensions that are
also realized in the horizontal field, (both chords are built in
stacking thirds plus the adjustment I spoke about), the 'dominant-
diminished' voicing that is staff generated, follows the voicing on
the C tonality ( in my previous post) as such, bass to top: D F Ab B C
Eb Gb A, but this needs to be adjusted by octave displacements
concerning certain intervals as such: D F# A C Eb Fnatch G# B.  This
shows you, staffwise, the fully loaded altered dom, which you are
interested in. It has three enharmonic equivalents, as you already
know, F7alt, G#7(Ab7alt), B7alt. But each of these, become enharmonic
substitutions, because the roots dictate separate functions when used
independently. It is this root function that you want to study. I
would imagine. You look at your staff-generated voicing (the voicing
yielding all the extensions that you wanted to study and codify) and
you begin thinning out from the density. And here is where you form
your own choice of voicings, deleting and/or leaving in tones (utilize
tones from other cycles) as need be according to function.

